      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software used for FEA (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) is validated under an ISO 13485-compliant QMS with documented version control, regression testing, and change control records.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is maintained under a documented software QMS. Version control logs, regression test results, and release notes were reviewed and found compliant with the required gradation level for a Medium model risk application."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems representative of the physics (large-displacement beam bending, contact mechanics) are solved and compared against analytical or published reference solutions with <1% error.",
      "rationale": "Three benchmark problems — cantilever beam deflection, Hertzian contact, and bolt-preload simulation — were executed in Ansys 2022 R2. All results agreed with reference solutions within 0.6%, confirming numerical code correctness at the required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates that QoI (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) change by <2% between the production mesh and a 1.5× refined mesh.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh refinement study was conducted across three mesh densities (coarse, medium, fine). QoI values changed by 1.1% (stiffness), 0.8% (yield force), and 1.4% (force at 40 mm) between the medium and fine meshes, confirming discretization error is below the 2% threshold."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Nonlinear solver residuals converge to below 1e-4 for all load steps; energy residuals below 1e-3.",
      "rationale": "Force and displacement convergence residuals were monitored across all 120 load increments. All residuals converged below 5e-5 (force) and 8e-4 (energy), meeting the acceptance criterion."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs, boundary conditions, and material assignments are independently reviewed by a second analyst; discrepancies resolved before results are accepted.",
      "rationale": "An independent senior analyst reviewed all model inputs, boundary condition specifications, material property assignments, and contact definitions against the simulation plan. Two minor discrepancies in contact stiffness scaling were identified and corrected prior to production runs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model (bilinear isotropic hardening) and contact formulation (augmented Lagrangian) are justified by literature precedent and sensitivity analysis confirming insensitivity to alternative formulations within ±5%.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening is well-established for Ti-6Al-4V under quasi-static loading. A sensitivity study comparing linear elastic, bilinear isotropic hardening, and Ramberg-Osgood formulations showed QoI variation of 3.2% maximum, within the ±5% tolerance. Augmented Lagrangian contact is standard for this class of problem."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties (E, σ_y, σ_u, tangent modulus) sourced from certified coupon tests on the same material lot as the test constructs; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties were derived from tensile coupon tests (n=5) on material from the same heat lot as the N=11 test constructs. CMM measurements of screw and rod geometry were used directly as model inputs. Uncertainty in material properties propagated through a Monte Carlo analysis confirms QoI uncertainty bounds are within acceptance criteria."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 experimental constructs tested; constructs are production-representative (same material lot, manufacturing process, and assembly procedure as commercial device).",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs were assembled from production-representative components (same material lot, machining process, and assembly torque specification as the commercial 7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screw). Testing was distributed across two independent laboratories to assess inter-laboratory variability."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios including at least two load levels or construct configurations.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single ASTM F1717 standardized condition (static compression-bending at 5° offset). Only one test condition was evaluated, which does not span the full range of clinically relevant configurations. This factor is below the required level; this gap is acknowledged and accepted given the strong agreement between FEA and experiment at the tested condition."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions, loading) are demonstrably equivalent to experimental conditions; all deviations quantified and their effect on QoI bounded.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared comparing each model input to the corresponding experimental measurement. All geometric inputs matched CMM data within 0.05 mm. Applied displacement boundary conditions replicated the test fixture kinematics. No unquantified deviations were identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all QoI; percentage difference < 10% for all QoI.",
      "rationale": "All three QoI met both acceptance criteria: stiffness E/uval=0.84 (diff 2.1%), yield force E/uval=1.12 (diff 4.3%), force at 40 mm E/uval=1.43 (diff 6.1%). The validation comparison is considered satisfactory."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the clinical failure mode of interest (screw or rod fracture under cyclic loading) and are the same quantities used in the regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three quantities specified in ASTM F1717 as primary performance metrics. These directly characterize the structural integrity of the construct under the worst-case bending scenario and are the quantities reported in the 510(k) submission."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
